```{r, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(collapse = TRUE, comment = "#>", fig.path = "figure/",
                      fig.width = 5, fig.height = 5, dpi = 96, error = FALSE)
```

[Alpha Earth Foundations](https://source.coop/tge-labs/aef) (AEF) publishes
annual geospatial embeddings as **64-band Int8 Cloud-Optimised GeoTIFFs**: each
band is one dimension of a learned per-pixel embedding, quantised to a signed
byte and decoded with a nonlinear, sign-preserving transform,
`((x / 127.5)^2) * sign(x)`.

Tens of bands in one file is exactly what `lazy_cog()` is for. Where
`lazy_dataset()` opens each band separately, `lazy_cog()` routes the read through
[cptkirk](https://belian-earth.github.io/cptkirk/), whose async-tiff reader opens
the tile **once** and streams all 64 band planes concurrently. This vignette
reads one tile, resamples to 30 m, dequantises on the read, and renders three
arbitrary bands as a false-colour composite.

## Read and dequantise

```{r read, message = FALSE}
library(garry)

# One AEF annual tile (Source Cooperative, public, no auth). UTM 36S, ~10 m.
tile <- paste0("https://data.source.coop/tge-labs/aef/v1/annual/2021/36S/",
               "xekh5rjs4wg6wb9b4-0000000000-0000000000.tiff")

# A 30 m grid over a ~15 km window. resampling = "average" downsamples from the
# ~10 m native grid, preserving the local embedding geometry while cutting the
# pixel count ~9x -- far lighter to hold in memory than a native-resolution read.
grid <- grid_spec("EPSG:32736",
                  extent = c(510000, 8540000, 525360, 8555360),
                  dims = c(512L, 512L), dtype = "f32")

embeddings <- lazy_cog(tile, grid, resampling = "average") |>
  lazy_map(fn = dequantize_aef, dtype = "f32")

embeddings
```

`lazy_cog()` records a lazy 64-band dataset; nothing is fetched yet.
`dequantize_aef()` is applied as a map, which garry fuses onto the read so the
nonlinear decode runs on-device, not as a separate pass.

## Collect three bands and plot

Pick three arbitrary embedding dimensions and collect just those: the band-axis
subset means only those three are ever computed.

```{r plot}
garry_daemons()
cube <- collect(embeddings[c("b7", "b21", "b48")])
garry_daemons(0, 0)

dim(cube)   # 512 x 512 x 3

# false-colour: rescale each band to [0, 1] for display
rescale <- function(x) { r <- range(x, na.rm = TRUE); (x - r[1]) / diff(r) }
rgb <- array(vapply(seq_len(3), function(i) rescale(cube[, , i]),
                    numeric(512 * 512)), dim = c(512, 512, 3))
plot(as.raster(rgb), interpolate = FALSE)
```

Neighbouring pixels of similar land cover carry similar embeddings, so the
false-colour image segments the landscape into coherent regions: the structure
the embeddings encode. The same dequantised dataset feeds any downstream verb --
a band-axis PCA (`reduce_over(over = "band")` with `band_project()`), a
similarity search, or a classifier fit on the collected array.
